1 judgment of a court for some penal offense.
2 (d)[3.] Persons who have been determined by a court of competent
3 jurisdiction to be mentally incompetent and who have not retained their voting rights
4 or had those rights restored[Idiots and insane persons].
5 (2) Persons convicted in any court of competent jurisdiction of a felony which
6 does not involve treason, bribery in an election, election fraud, a violent felony offense,
7 a felony sexual offense, a criminal offense against a child, or a Class A or Class B
8 felony who have not been previously restored to their civil rights by executive pardon
9 shall have their civil rights automatically restored after completion of any sentence
10 including imprisonment, probation, and parole.
11 (3) Persons who have had their right to vote or civil rights previously restored
12 under this section and who subsequently have been convicted in any court of
13 competent jurisdiction of any felony shall not have the right to vote or have their civil
14 rights automatically restored until completion of any sentence including imprisonment,
15 probation, and parole for the subsequent offense, unless they are restored to their civil
16 rights by executive pardon.
17 Section 3. This amendment shall be submitted to the voters of the
18 Commonwealth for their ratification or rejection at the time and in the manner provided
19 for under Sections 256 and 257 of the Constitution, KRS 118.415, and Sections 4 and 5
20 of this Act.
21 Section 4. Notwithstanding any provision of KRS 118.415 to the contrary, the
22 Secretary of State shall cause the entirety of the question in Section 1 of this Act and the
23 entirety of the proposed amendment to the Constitution of Kentucky contained in Section
24 2 of this Act to be published at least one time in a newspaper of general circulation
25 published in this state, and shall also cause to be published at the same time and in the
26 same manner the fact that the amendment will be submitted to the voters for their
27 acceptance or rejection at the next regular election at which members of the General
